<subSubSection pageId="7" pageNumber="394" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1436,327,823]" box="[151,1022,327,355]" pageId="7" pageNumber="394">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,299,327,354]" pageId="7" pageNumber="394">Description:</emphasis>
Adults yellowish orange. Wing expanse: 
<quantity box="[765,886,328,355]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.5" metricValueMax="3.6" metricValueMin="3.4" pageId="7" pageNumber="394" unit="mm" value="35.0" valueMax="36.0" valueMin="34.0">34–36 mm</quantity>
(
<figureCitation box="[901,1008,328,355]" captionStart="FIGURES 7–10" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1944,1969]" captionTargetBox="[159,1431,821,1912]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[151,1437,813,1924]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 7–10. Adults.7, Caldubotys caldusalis, gen. &amp; comb. nov., ♂, NE India, Sikkim; 8, ditto, ♀, NE India, Sikkim; 9, Endocrossis flavibasalis, ♂, NE India, Mizoram; 10, Pyrausta purpuralis, ♂ (©Lewis, C. British Lepidoptera, https://british- lepidoptera.weebly.com/007-pyrausta purpuralis.html.)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3255393/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="394">Figs. 7, 8</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1436,327,823]" box="[199,771,364,391]" pageId="7" pageNumber="394">
<emphasis box="[199,260,364,390]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="394">Head</emphasis>
. Concolourous with adults. Antennae simple.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1436,327,823]" pageId="7" pageNumber="394">
<emphasis box="[199,280,400,426]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="394">Thorax</emphasis>
. Forewing with costa and basal area slightly suffused with reddish brown, an oblique, outwardly curved ante-medial line, distinctly curved towards inner side from below cell; speak in cell; a dark spot at discocellular; indistinct excurved post-medial line, out-curved between veins M 
<subScript attach="left" box="[865,873,490,504]" fontSize="6" pageId="7" pageNumber="394">2</subScript>
and 2A; a prominent curved sub-marginal spotted line; dark marginal line. Hindwing with basal area straw yellow; an ante-medial line starting from a speck in cell; a curved, dentate medial line from a dark spot at discocellular; followed by an indistinct post-medial line, cilia of both wings fuscous at tip. In females, markings are slightly prominent.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1436,327,823]" pageId="7" pageNumber="394">
<emphasis box="[199,363,616,642]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="394">Male genitalia</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[377,515,616,642]" captionStart="FIGURES 19–23" captionStartId="5.[151,264,1739,1764]" captionTargetBox="[157,1436,187,1708]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[151,1436,181,1719]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 19–23. Male genitalia. 19, 20, Neobotyodes crocopteralis, gen. &amp; comb. nov. 21–23, Caldubotys caldusalis gen. &amp; comb. nov." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3255397/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="394">Figs. 21–23</figureCitation>
). Uncus petiolated, swan head shaped, tip hairy; tegumen very broad; valvae broad with costa well differentiated, apex rounded; transtilla weakly sclerotised; saccus pointed; aedeagus elongated; vesica with two sclerotised plates.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1436,327,823]" box="[199,1121,724,751]" pageId="7" pageNumber="394">
<emphasis box="[199,390,724,750]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="394">Female genitalia</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[405,489,724,750]" captionStart="FIGURES 29–32" captionStartId="7.[151,264,1968,1993]" captionTargetBox="[168,1420,857,1937]" captionTargetId="figure@7.[151,1436,844,1949]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURES 29–32. Female genitalia, 29, Botyodes asialis; 30, Botyodes principalis; 31, Neobotyodes crocopteralis, gen. &amp; comb. nov.; 32, Caldubotys caldusalis, gen. &amp; comb. nov." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3255401/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="394">Fig. 32</figureCitation>
). Ductus bursae sclerotised; corpus bursae long, tubular.
</paragraph>
